    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-01-28T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-01-28T19:00:00-05:00" n="237"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d237">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">352.115 Eastern States Petroleum Co./29:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bowers</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">Then in France</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-28T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 28, 1938—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>B–404. Your 428, January 25, 1 p.m. Telegram from Fisher<note n="16"
                        xml:id="d237fn16">Not printed.</note> reports captain of <hi rend="italic"
                        >Nantucket Chief</hi> taken ashore under arrest for trial on unspecified
                    charges. Please communicate with Franco authorities and request prompt action
                    for release of captain.</p>
                <p>For your information owners of vessel have suggested to Department that release
                    of vessel might be expedited if assistant naval attaché at Paris were authorized
                    to go to Salamanca to take up matter with Franco authorities. It appears that
                    vice president of company <pb facs="0274" n="266" xml:id="pg_266"/> is
                    personally acquainted with assistant naval attaché at Paris. We have made it
                    clear to the owners that we do not favor such a visit.</p>
                <p>We shall appreciate an indication of when a reply may be expected from Franco
                    authorities regarding release of ship. In taking up with them matter of
                    captain’s arrest you should emphasize our interest in obtaining the release of
                    this American vessel. The Department will appreciate any suggestions that you
                    may wish to make as to other means of expediting release.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
